was to meet me Friday morning on the Square of the Arts in frontof the Russian Museum near the statue of Pushkin erected some ten yearsbefore by a committee of weathermen. An Intourist folder had yielded atinted photograph of the spot. The meteorological associations of themonument predominated over its cultural ones. Frock-coated Pushkin, theright-side lap of his garment permanently agitated by the Nevan breezerather than by the violence of lyrical afflatus, stands looking upward andto the left